 of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Alis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Allis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Allis","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Alis</i>, <i>Alice</i> (Old French <i>Adeliz</i>, <i>Ahelis</i>, <i>Aalis</i>, <i>Aliz</i>). <i>Alice</i>, together with its pet form <i>Alison</i>, was one of the most popular names in both England and Scotland from the 13th century until the end of the medieval period. The personal name is of ancient Germanic origin, brought to England from France by the Normans; it is a shortened form of ancient Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>, which is composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>haid</i> ‘‘rank, worth’’."]}]},{"name":"Joseph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the biblical Hebrew name <i>Yosef</i>, meaning ‘(God) shall add (another son)’. This was borne by the favourite son of Jacob, whose brothers became jealous of him and sold him into slavery (Genesis 37). He was taken to Egypt, where he rose to become chief steward to Pharaoh, and was eventually reconciled to his brothers when they came to buy corn during a seven-year famine (Genesis 43–7). In the New Testament <i>Joseph</i> is the name of the husband of the Virgin Mary. It is also borne by a rich Jew, Joseph of Arimathea (Matthew 27:57; Mark 15:43; Luke 23:50; John 19:38), who took Jesus down from the Cross, wrapped him in a shroud, and buried him in a rock tomb. According to medieval legend, Joseph of Arimathea brought the Holy Grail to Britain. The name was uncommon in Britain in the Middle Ages but was revived in the mid 16th century and had become popular by the 1630s, remaining so ever since."],"variants":[{"name":"Josef","meanings":[", Dutch, Scandinavian, and Czech spelling of   Joseph  , now also in use in the English‐speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joseph De Alis was born in 1100, in Normandy, France, his father, William De Alis, was 40 and his mother, Mrs. Elizabeth De Alis, was 38. He had at least 1 son with Solounce De Alis. He died in 1176, in his hometown, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1100–1176":"1100–1176","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1130–1210":"1130–1210","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1062–1131":"1062–1131","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","1062":"1062","1060":"1060","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bar Alston, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1100–1176":"1100–1176","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1130–1210":"1130–1210","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1062–1131":"1062–1131","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","1062":"1062","1060":"1060","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Bar Alston, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska"},"fr":{"1100–1176":"1100–1176","1100–1178":"1100–1178","1130–1210":"1130–1210","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1062–1131":"1062–1131","1178":"1178","1100":"1100","1210":"1210","1176":"1176","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","1062":"1062","1060":"1060","Normandie, France":"Normandie, France","Bar Alston, Devon, England":"Devon, A